         <div type="transcription">
            <p>
<lb corresp="#a5"/><w>kwäsartse</w></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">in a string (?)</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="lingcomment">The gloss is identified by <bibl><title corresp="ref:filliozatandkuno1938"/><citedRange>29</citedRange></bibl> as TB, but no interpretation is offered. <hi>kwäsartse</hi> reminds of TB <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-ioltoch263"/>: a4 <hi>k<hi rend="subscript">u</hi>sär</hi> (arch) as well as of <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a378"/> <hi>kusraṃ</hi> (<bibl><title corresp="ref:hilmarsson1996"/><citedRange>195</citedRange></bibl>). For <hi>k<hi rend="subscript">u</hi>sär</hi>, <bibl><title corresp="ref:adams2013a"/><citedRange>199</citedRange></bibl> cautiously suggests 'braid' on the basis of TA <hi>kusraṃ</hi> and points out that an alternative word division <hi>k<hi rend="subscript">u</hi>särsā</hi> would also be possible, in which case it could be a plural (a perl. sg. would of course be an additional posibility). While <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-ioltoch263"/> is too fragmentary, the context of <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a378"/> suggests 'hairdress' (<bibl><title corresp="ref:itkin2011"/><citedRange>51</citedRange></bibl>). Carling's 'braid of hair' (<bibl><title corresp="ref:carlingetal2009"/><citedRange>157b-158</citedRange></bibl>a) would seem to fit the context better, but has to cope with the problem that it needs <hi>kusraṃ</hi> to be a nom.du., while it can only be a loc.sg., as pointed out by Itkin (p.c.). The precise meaning of Skt. <hi>sāvadānaṃ</hi> is uncertain, and the semantic connection with TA <hi>kusraṃ</hi>, if related, is not obvious. Possible semantic links to consider are the ones between e.g. 'strand of hair, string' and 'uninterruptedly', or between 'hair braid' and 'in regular order'. In any case, <hi>kwäsartse</hi> must be an adjective derived from the noun <hi>k<hi rend="subscript">u</hi>sar*</hi>, here apparently in adverbial use.</note><note type="philcomment">Glosses Skt. <hi>(sāvadā)naṃ</hi> 'in regular order, uninterruptedly' (corrected reading due to Klaus Wille, p.c.).</note></p>
         </div>
