               <item n="m_lingcomment_old">&lt;p&gt;The gloss is identified by [[Filliozat and Kuno 1938]]: 29 as TB, but no interpretation is offered. &lt;i&gt;kwäsartse&lt;/i&gt; reminds of TB [[IOL Toch 263]]: a4 &lt;i&gt;k&lt;sub&gt;u&lt;/sub&gt;sär&lt;/i&gt; (arch) as well as of [[A 378]]: 2 &lt;i&gt;kusraṃ&lt;/i&gt; ([[Hilmarsson 1996]]: 195). For &lt;i&gt;k&lt;sub&gt;u&lt;/sub&gt;sär&lt;/i&gt;, [[Adams, 2DoT]]: 199 cautiously suggests 'braid' on the basis of TA &lt;i&gt;kusraṃ&lt;/i&gt; and points out that an alternative word division &lt;i&gt;k&lt;sub&gt;u&lt;/sub&gt;särsā&lt;/i&gt; would also be possible, in which case it could be a plural (a perl. sg. would of course be an additional posibility). While [[IOL Toch 263]] is too fragmentary, the context of [[A 378]] suggests 'hairdress' ([[Itkin 2011]]: 51). Carling's 'braid of hair' ([[Carling, DThTA]]: 157b-158a) would seem to fit the context better, but has to cope with the problem that it needs &lt;i&gt;kusraṃ&lt;/i&gt; to be a nom.du., while it can only be a loc.sg., as pointed out by Itkin (p.c.). The precise meaning of Skt. &lt;i&gt;sāvadānaṃ&lt;/i&gt; is uncertain, and the semantic connection with TA &lt;i&gt;kusraṃ&lt;/i&gt;, if related, is not obvious. Possible semantic links to consider are the ones between e.g. 'strand of hair, string' and 'uninterruptedly', or between 'hair braid' and 'in regular order'. In any case, &lt;i&gt;kwäsartse&lt;/i&gt; must be an adjective derived from the noun &lt;i&gt;k&lt;sub&gt;u&lt;/sub&gt;sar*&lt;/i&gt;, here apparently in adverbial use.&lt;/p&gt;</item>
